def: Behavior like that of a fox; [Obs.] Chaucer.
A dance in moderate twofold time, invented by the French in thereign of Louis XIV.; -- now mostly found in suites of pieces, likethose of Bach and Handel.

A person who is deaf and dumb; one who, through deprivation ordefect of hearing, has either failed the acquire the power of speech,or has lost it. [See Illust. of Dactylology.]Deaf-mutes are still so called, even when, by artificial methods,they have been taught to speak imperfectly.
A division of Mollusca remarkable for the bilateral symmetry ofthe organs and the arrangement of the nerves.
In the form or manner of aphorisms; pithily.
A species of tern, esp. the sooty tern (Sterna fuliginosa) ofthe West Indies. In the Bahama Islands the name is applied to thetropic bird, PhaÃ«thon flavirostris.
A large stone set upright in olden times as a memorial ormonument. Many, of unknown date, are found in Brittany and throughoutNorthern Europe.
To utter in a grumbling manner; to mutter.
A kind of pessary of medicated wool or cotton, formerly used.
